            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Kapoor\u2019s appreciation for aesthetics was woven into his upbringing. The son of an architect father and a textile designer mother who emigrated from Mumbai to Fremont, his childhood home was a study in structure and color. While his parents encouraged a stable career, they filled his life with art books and trips to museums, inadvertently planting a seed. The turning point came at sixteen during a family trip to India. Standing within the Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Vastu Sangrahalaya in Mumbai, surrounded by ancient sculptures and intricate miniature paintings, Rohan realized that objects held stories. He decided his life\u2019s work would be to tell them.\n\nThis revelation propelled him to study Art History at UC Santa Cruz and later pursue an MFA in Museum Studies at the University of San Francisco, a move that finally brought him to the city he had admired from across the bay. After graduating, he landed a role as an Exhibitions Coordinator for a dynamic contemporary art gallery in SoMa. His days are a flurry of emails with artists, meticulous planning for installations, and the creative problem-solving required to bring a vision to life.\n\nNow, Rohan\u2019s life is quintessentially San Francisco. He lives in a rent-stabilized apartment in the Mission District, filled with plants and prints from artist friends. His 2.8-mile commute is a daily ritual on his well-loved bicycle, a blur of colorful murals, morning fog, and the hum of city life. His evenings are often spent with his partner, Clara, a graphic designer he met at a gallery opening. They explore new taco spots, attend film screenings at the Roxie, or simply sketch in Dolores Park.\n\nRohan\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep; he sees its layers of history, activism, and reinvention as a living museum. While he enjoys the hands-on nature of his current role, he dreams of becoming a full-fledged Curator. His ultimate aspiration is to curate a major exhibition that bridges contemporary South Asian diasporic art with Western modernism, a project that would honor his heritage and his chosen home."
